<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1934-02-16T14:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1934-02-16T14:00:00-05:00" n="468" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d468">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">251.11 Insull, Samuel/339:
                                Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in Greece</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">MacVeagh</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Athens</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-02-16T21:00:00+02:00">February 16, 1934—9
                                        p.m.</date><lb/>[Received February 16—5:07 p.m.]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>18. The Foreign Minister verbally requested me this afternoon to
                                inform you that his Government sincerely desires and intends to
                                expel Insull but that owing to the unusually inclement weather now
                                prevailing and the fugitive’s physical condition it believes it is
                                only humane to allow him to remain from 10 days to 2 weeks longer
                                and begs you to have patience. I asked Mr. Maximos<note n="29" xml:id="d468fn29">D. Maximos, Greek Minister for Foreign
                                    Affairs.</note> if this meant that expulsion would then
                                definitely take place and he replied in the affirmative.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">MacVeagh</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>